### 6. Physics Simulation Loop (`a0nl` → `simulateForces`)

```javascript
function simulateForces() {
    // Node-node repulsion (inverse square)
    for (i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        for (j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
            dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
            dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
            dist = Math.sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1;
            force = config.universal / (dist * dist);
            // Apply equal and opposite forces
            nodes[i].vx += (dx / dist) * force;
            nodes[j].vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
            // ... same for vy
        }
    }

    // Spring forces along edges
    for (p = 0; p < edges.length; p++) {
        A = findNode(edges[p].a);
        B = findNode(edges[p].b);
        displacement = dist - edges[p].rest;
        force = edges[p].k * displacement;
        // Apply spring force to both nodes
    }

    // Integration + centering force + damping
    for (s = 0; s < nodes.length; s++) {
        nodes[s].vx += (400 - nodes[s].x) * config.universal; // center pull
        nodes[s].vy += (300 - nodes[s].y) * config.universal;
        nodes[s].vx *= config.amplitudeDamping;  // damping
        nodes[s].vy *= config.amplitudeDamping;
        nodes[s].x += nodes[s].vx;  // integrate position
        nodes[s].y += nodes[s].vy;
    }
}
```

### 7. Particle System (`a0nk` → `spawnParticle`, `a0nM` → `updateParticles`)

```javascript
function spawnParticle() {
    if (particles.length >= config.streamCount) return;
    var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
    var angle = Math.random() * TWO_PI;
    var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT2;
    particles.push({
        x: source.x, y: source.y,
        vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
        vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
        age: 0,
        maxAge: 30 + Math.random() * 60,
        size: 0.8 + Math.random() * GOLDEN_RATIO * SQRT2
    });
}

function updateParticles() {
    for (r = particles.length - 1; r >= 0; r--) {
        p = particles[r];
        p.vx *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
        p.vy *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
        p.x += p.vx;
        p.y += p.vy;
        p.age++;
        if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(r, 1);
    }
}
```

### 8. Camera Smoothing

```javascript
function updateCamera() {
    camera.x += (target.x - camera.x) * config.drag;
    camera.y += (target.y - camera.y) * config.drag;
    camera.zoom += (target.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.drag;
}
```

### 9. Main Loop

```javascript
function tick() {
    simulateForces();
    updateParticles();
    updateCamera();
    frameCount++;
    if (frameCount % 2 === 0) spawnParticle();  // spawn every other frame
}
setInterval(tick, 16);  // ~60fps
```

## Summary

**This is a force-directed graph simulation** with:
- **6 nodes** connected by **8 springs** forming a network topology
- **Particle effects** that emit from random nodes and fade over time
- **Smooth camera** tracking
- **Physics**: node repulsion + spring attraction + center gravity + velocity damping
- **Anti-debugging protection** that makes the code self-check for tampering

The mathematical constants `0.283` (TWO_PI ≈ no, likely a custom constant), `0.618` (golden ratio), and `0.707` (√2/2) are used for particle spawning aesthetics.

It's essentially a **headless physics engine** — there's no rendering code here, suggesting it either feeds data to a separate renderer or this is one module of a larger visualization system.
